===================================================
TEST RESULTS / ADJUSTMENTS
===================================================

- if the milk has reduced to a thick sludge, but the rice grains are still crunchy in the middle,
    the heat may have been too high or you may have added to teh sugar too early. 
    don't cook any longer, you'll just burn the pudding. 
    add 1/2 cup h ot water (water penetrates better than milk at this stage).
    cover and cook on lowest possible setting for 10 minutes
    the steam pressure will force hydration
- if the pudding separates into a solid mass of rice and a pool of watery liquid after cooling,
    this is retrogradation gone wrong. If the putting was cooked until it was too thick (over-gelatinized),
    the starch network becomes too tight upon cooling. As the amylose re-bonds, they squeeze water out of the matrix. 
    This is why you stop cooking when the pudding is still soupy. 
- if there are small yellow specks in the pudding it means the egg yolks were heated about 180F. 
    at this temperature the protieins (ovotransferrin) tighten aggressively, squeezing out water and fat, 
    resulting in solid curds. 
    you can try vigorously whisking it to re-emulsify the yolk lipids. 
- if a brown layer stuck to the bottom of the pan and there's a bitter acrid taste throughout,
    it's because milk solids settled to the bottom adn burned. 
    it may have been because agitation was insiffucient. 
    do not scrape the bottom. if you smell burning, pour the unburnt top layer of pudding into a new clean pot immediately.


